{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe enriched sidecars (stories A–C) and the existing attestations are reachable today only via\nscattered internal helpers, and there is no single call that returns a ticket's FULL retained review\nhistory or resolves its associated code reviews. The follow-on audit UI epic and any script need one\ndocumented read surface.\n\n## What\n\nA read layer that, for a ticket id, returns: (a) the full retained history (not just latest) of\nplan-review sidecars; (b) the completion attestation plus any completion sidecar record; (c) the\nassociated code reviews, resolved via the ticket's inbound `relates_to` links from `code_review`\ntickets, each with its full sidecar history. Exposed as a library function, a CLI command, and a\nread-only MCP tool.\n\n## Data contract (the returned typed dict)\n\n`audit_trail(ticket_id)` returns a `TypedDict` with EXACT key names and nullability:\n\n```python\nclass AuditTrail(TypedDict):\n    ticket: dict                 # the ticket's current details (from rebar.show)\n    plan_reviews: list[dict]     # full retained plan-review sidecar history, newest-first; [] if none\n    completion: dict | None      # completion attestation + sidecar record; None if no record\n    code_reviews: list[dict]     # each: {ticket_id, sidecars: list[dict]} — a linked code_review\n                                 # ticket + its own newest-first sidecar history; [] if no\n                                 # relates_to links\n```\n\n- `plan_reviews` is ALWAYS a list (empty `[]` when the ticket has no plan-review sidecars), newest\n  first.\n- `completion` is EITHER a dict (when a completion attestation or sidecar record exists) OR `None`.\n- `code_reviews` is ALWAYS a list (empty `[]` when no `code_review` ticket links to this ticket via\n  `relates_to`); each entry carries its OWN sidecar history list.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py` and `src/rebar/llm/code_review/sidecar.py` — add\n  `all_review_results(ticket)` history enumerators (walk the ticket's `REVIEW_RESULT` events\n  newest→oldest, schema-tolerant), complementing the existing `latest_*` readers.\n- New `src/rebar/audit/read.py` — an `audit_trail(ticket_id)` aggregator composing the plan /\n  completion / code-review histories, resolving code reviews via the ticket's `relates_to` links\n  (reusing `rebar.show` / `rebar.list_tickets`), returning the `AuditTrail` typed dict above.\n- CLI registration: `rebar audit show <ticket> [--output json]`. Register an `audit` intercept in\n  `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py::main` (following the established owns-its-own-`--help` intercept\n  pattern used by `_workflow` / `_llm` / `_criteria`), dispatching to an `audit_cli(rest)` handler\n  (new `src/rebar/_cli/_audit_commands.py`), and add `\"audit\"` to the set returned by\n  `src/rebar/_cli/_help.py::known_subcommands` so it is a recognized subcommand.\n- MCP read-tool registration: add a read-only `audit_trail(ticket_id)` tool inside\n  `src/rebar/_mcp_reads.py::register_read_tools` (decorated with `@mcp.tool(annotations=_ANN\n  [\"READ_ONLY\"])`, like the other read tools), so it is available even under `REBAR_MCP_READONLY=1`.\n\n## Approach rationale\n\nA single aggregator over the existing readers + the existing `relates_to` links reuses the linkage\nthe reviewbot already writes (`emit_code_review_artifact` links each code-review artifact\n`relates_to` its work ticket), so no new linking mechanism is introduced — the read layer only\ntraverses links that already exist. The MCP tool is read-only so it is available regardless of\n`REBAR_MCP_READONLY`.\n\n## Compatibility & rollback\n\nPure addition (new readers + new command + new read-only tool); no existing behavior changes.\nSchema-tolerant readers accept both v1 and v2 records. Reverting removes the new surface with no\ndata impact.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `audit_trail(ticket_id)` returns a dict with EXACTLY the keys `ticket`, `plan_reviews`,\n      `completion`, `code_reviews`; `plan_reviews` and `code_reviews` are lists (newest-first,\n      `[]` when none), `completion` is `dict | None` (`None` when no record). Oracle: an integration\n      test seeding a ticket with multiple plan-review sidecars, a completion record, and a\n      `relates_to`-linked `code_review` ticket with its own sidecar, then asserting the exact key\n      set, the newest-first ordering of `plan_reviews`, that `completion` is a dict, and that\n      `code_reviews[0]` carries its own sidecar history; plus a companion assertion that a\n      bare ticket yields `plan_reviews == []`, `completion is None`, `code_reviews == []`.\n- [ ] `rebar audit show <ticket> --output json` prints the same structure. Oracle: a CLI subprocess\n      test (test-design §3 CLI) asserting on the emitted JSON's key set.\n- [ ] The MCP `audit_trail` tool returns the structure and is read-only (available even with\n      `REBAR_MCP_READONLY=1`). Oracle: a test invoking the tool handler under that env.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784075638968406001,"uuid":"27510398-9d0c-44d0-8116-8e7b3edb383f"}